<br>
<br>
Thirty Woomera detention centre escapees appeared in a packed Adelaide Magistrates Court, while two more were recaptured by accident when they flagged down an unmarked police bus.<br>
<br>
Twelve of the escapees remain on the run.<br>
<br>
The 30 men who appeared in court - Afghans, Iraqis, Iranians, and Turks - were greeted with waves and cheers from supporters who had earlier chanted, played drums and held banners outside the courthouse.<br>
<br>
Charged under the Federal Immigration Act with escaping from the outback facility, they were all granted bail today but would have to return to immigration detention.<br>
<br>
Bail conditions, however, entitle them to leave detention and move interstate if granted temporary visas by the immigration department.<br>
<br>
 Up to seven uniformed police officers stood watching proceedings in the courtroom at any one time, as well as court security officers, although they did not need to take any action.<br>
<br>
Magistrate Fred Field had to call for quiet in the courtroom several times.<br>
<br>
Appearing before the court individually or in pairs, some detainees responded to gestures of support by waving and blowing kisses as they were told their bail conditions by interpreters.<br>
<br>
They were part of a group of 50 detainees who escaped from Woomera during violent mass protests last Friday. Thirty-eight asylum seekers have since been recaptured or returned of their own volition.<br>
<br>
South Australian police said two detainees captured today were caught after hailing an unmarked police bus 38km north of Port Augusta.<br>
<br>
The bus was carrying police home after helping to control weekend protesters at Woomera.<br>
<br>
Assistant Commissioner Graham Brown told the ABC he expected other missing detainees would be found on the same route.<br>
<br>
"We'll continue to maintain our surveillance along that main road," he said.<br>
<br>
"In previous experiences we've found they do wander out onto the main roadway."<br>
<br>
Immigration Minister Philip Ruddock denied reports that some detainees were being punished for the weekend unrest through a range of measures, including solitary confinement and handcuffing.<br>
<br>
Mr Ruddock said there were no punishment measures used at Woomera other than restraints used to prevent people from committing suicide or attempting self-harm.<br>
<br>
He said people were only punished according to the law and through court proceedings.<br>
<br>
South Australian Premier Mike Rann was today critical of both protesters and the federal government.<br>
<br>
Mr Rann said while there were peaceful demonstrators there, there were others who behaved like hooligans, throwing urine and other missiles at police, which did enormous damage to the cause of the asylum seekers.<br>
<br>
But he said he could not believe Mr Ruddock's criticism of SA police.<br>
<br>
"I think Mr Ruddock needs to apologise," Mr Rann said.<br>
